# ── How a wallet reaches your KERIA (OOBI host) ─────────────────────────
# A wallet that scans an OOBI must be able to REACH KERIA over the network.
# Pick ONE of the setups below.

# ---- Option A: ngrok tunnel (default) — needs a free token + a free domain ----
# Opens an ngrok tunnel and advertises a STABLE public https url in OOBIs.
# Both values below are free, one-time signups at ngrok — and BOTH are required:
#   1. NGROK_AUTHTOKEN — https://dashboard.ngrok.com/get-started/your-authtoken
#   2. NGROK_DOMAIN    — reserve one free at https://dashboard.ngrok.com/domains
#
# Why a domain is required: KERIA bakes the advertised host into the agent at
# first boot. A reserved domain keeps that host STABLE, so a wallet connection
# survives restarts. (A random tunnel changes on every restart and silently
# breaks the connection — which is why we don't allow it.)
COMPOSE_PROFILES=tunnel
KERIA_PUBLIC_URL=ngrok
NGROK_AUTHTOKEN=
NGROK_DOMAIN=your-name.ngrok-free.app

# ---- Option B: production-style — Traefik + your own domain ----
# Mirrors Veridian's self-host pattern: a Traefik reverse proxy fronts the whole
# stack under ONE domain with HTTPS (Let's Encrypt), giving the wallet proper
# subdomains (keria, keria-boot, keria-ext, cred-issuance) and a real public
# schema host. Needs a public host with ports 80+443 and DNS A-records for those
# subdomains. Then:
#
#   COMPOSE_PROFILES=traefik
#   PUBLIC_DOMAIN=example.com
#   ACME_ADMIN_EMAIL=you@example.com
#
#   docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.traefik.yml up -d --build
#
# (No ngrok vars needed in this mode.)

# ---- Local only (no wallet) ----
# Leave both COMPOSE_PROFILES and KERIA_PUBLIC_URL empty for internal-only dev;
# the stack runs but a wallet cannot connect.
